comment.narrative:
The desired outcomes from this output  include: (1) Smallholder adaptive capacity for climate resilient agricultural practices strengthened; (2) Reduce vulnerability to droughts and floods; and (3) Mainstreaming climate change into national agricultural strategy/sectoral policy, including budgetary adjustments for replication and scaling up. By 2016, the following main activities towards these were achieved: 

1.	Installation of a total of 217 micro-drip Irrigation gardens:
a.	 44 organised groups and/or community gardens with each group with an average of 10 active members of mostly women-led groups;
b.	 54 schools with each school with an average of 200 learners; 
c.	119 individual farmers including Lead Farmers (79 females and 40 males);
d.	Training for individual farmers (16 males and 58 females);

2.	Promotion of Conservation Agricultural Practices:
a.	Provision of seeds of the which disaggregated data for male and female and number of households will only be available at the end of the 2016/17 planting season;
b.	Ripping services of a total of 229 hectares (29 male and 200 female headed households); and 
c.	Training for farmers including awareness raising  (36 males and 54 females);

3.	Development of a mentorship training programme; 

4.	Restoration of earth dams and wells:
a.	Four earth dams with each earth dam serving an average of 10 villages of a total of approximately 5,000 villagers were restored;
b.	Six hand-dug wells each serving an average of two villages were constructed;

5.	Other Project Activities (Consultations, administration including monitoring and evaluations, and training for project and MAWF staff members).
